1- Request flow

A user types www.foobar.com in their browser. The browser queries a DNS resolver, which looks up foobar.com and finds a www A record pointing to 8.8.8.8. The browser then opens a TCP connection to that IP and sends an HTTP request.

2- Component roles

Server — a physical or virtual machine with an OS, CPU, RAM, and storage. It listens for network connections and runs all the software below.
Domain name — a human-readable alias (foobar.com) that maps to the server's IP. Without it, users would need to remember 8.8.8.8. It also lets you change hosting without changing what users type.
DNS www record type — it's an A record (Address record). It maps the hostname www.foobar.com directly to an IPv4 address (8.8.8.8).
Web server (Nginx) — the front door. It accepts incoming HTTP/HTTPS connections, serves static files directly (images, CSS, JS), handles SSL termination, and forwards dynamic requests to the application server. This separation keeps things fast.
Application server — executes your business logic (PHP, Python, Node, etc.). It reads the request, runs code, queries the database, and builds a response to send back through Nginx.
Database (MySQL) — persistent storage. The app server queries it to read/write users, posts, sessions — anything that needs to survive across requests.
Communication protocol — the server communicates with the user's computer over HTTP/HTTPS, which runs on top of TCP/IP. Nginx handles TLS so the connection is encrypted end-to-end.

3- Problems with this design

Single Point of Failure (SPOF) — the entire site goes down if the server fails (hardware fault, OS crash, network outage). There's no redundancy anywhere.
Maintenance downtime — deploying new code typically requires restarting Nginx or the app server. During that window, the site is unreachable. With only one server there's nowhere to shift traffic.
No horizontal scaling — if traffic spikes, you can only scale up (bigger CPU/RAM) on that one machine, which has hard limits and costs. You can't add more servers to distribute load without redesigning the architecture entirely.
